82 return strncmp(Str, MAI.getCommentString().data(), 0
83 MAI.getCommentString().size()) == 0; 0

85 ----
86 /// Measure the specified inline asm to determine an approximation of its ----
87 /// length. ----
88 /// Comments (which run till the next SeparatorString or newline) do not ----
89 /// count as an instruction. ----
90 /// Any other non-whitespace text is considered an instruction, with ----
91 /// multiple instructions separated by SeparatorString or newlines. ----
92 /// Variable-length instructions are not handled here; this function ----
93 /// may be overloaded in the target code to do that. ----
94 /// We implement a special case of the .space directive which takes only a ----
95 /// single integer argument in base 10 that is the size in bytes. This is a ----
96 /// restricted form of the GAS directive in that we only interpret ----
97 /// simple--i.e. not a logical or arithmetic expression--size values without ----
98 /// the optional fill value. This is primarily used for creating arbitrary ----
99 /// sized inline asm blocks for testing purposes. ----
100 unsigned TargetInstrInfo::getInlineAsmLength( 0
101 const char *Str, ----
102 const MCAsmInfo &MAI, const TargetSubtargetInfo *STI) const { ----
103 // Count the number of instructions in the asm. ----
104 bool AtInsnStart = true; 0
105 unsigned Length = 0; 0
106 const unsigned MaxInstLength = MAI.getMaxInstLength(STI); 0
107 for (; *Str; ++Str) { 0
108 if (*Str == '\n' || strncmp(Str, MAI.getSeparatorString(), 0
109 strlen(MAI.getSeparatorString())) == 0) { ----
110 AtInsnStart = true; 0
111 } else if (isAsmComment(Str, MAI)) { 0
112 // Stop counting as an instruction after a comment until the next ----
113 // separator. ----
114 AtInsnStart = false; 0
115 } ----
116 ----
117 if (AtInsnStart && !isSpace(static_cast(*Str))) { 0
118 unsigned AddLength = MaxInstLength; 0
119 if (strncmp(Str, ".space", 6) == 0) { 0
120 char *EStr; ----
121 int SpaceSize; ----
122 SpaceSize = strtol(Str + 6, &EStr, 10); 0
123 SpaceSize = SpaceSize < 0 ? 0 : SpaceSize; 0
124 while (*EStr != '\n' && isSpace(static_cast(*EStr))) 0
125 ++EStr; 0
126 if (*EStr == '\0' || *EStr == '\n' || 0
127 isAsmComment(EStr, MAI)) // Successfully parsed .space argument 0
128 AddLength = SpaceSize; 0
129 } ----
130 Length += AddLength; 0
131 AtInsnStart = false; 0
132 } ----
133 } ----
134 ----
135 return Length; 0
136 } ----

140 void ----
141 TargetInstrInfo::ReplaceTailWithBranchTo(MachineBasicBlock::iterator Tail, 0
142 MachineBasicBlock *NewDest) const { ----
143 MachineBasicBlock *MBB = Tail->getParent(); 0
144 ----
145 // Remove all the old successors of MBB from the CFG. ----

263 bool TargetInstrInfo::fixCommutedOpIndices(unsigned &ResultIdx1, 0
264 unsigned &ResultIdx2, ----
265 unsigned CommutableOpIdx1, ----
266 unsigned CommutableOpIdx2) { ----
267 if (ResultIdx1 == CommuteAnyOperandIndex && 0

275 ResultIdx1 = CommutableOpIdx1; 0

277 return false; 0
278 } else if (ResultIdx2 == CommuteAnyOperandIndex) { 0
279 if (ResultIdx1 == CommutableOpIdx1) 0
280 ResultIdx2 = CommutableOpIdx2; 0
281 else if (ResultIdx1 == CommutableOpIdx2) 0
282 ResultIdx2 = CommutableOpIdx1; 0
283 else ----
284 return false; 0
285 } else ----
286 // Check that the result operand indices match the given commutable ----
287 // operand indices. ----
288 return (ResultIdx1 == CommutableOpIdx1 && ResultIdx2 == CommutableOpIdx2) || 0
289 (ResultIdx1 == CommutableOpIdx2 && ResultIdx2 == CommutableOpIdx1); 0
290 ----
291 return true; 0

296 unsigned &SrcOpIdx2) const { ----

303 ----
304 // This assumes v0 = op v1, v2 and commuting would swap v1 and v2. If this ----
305 // is not true, then the target must implement this. ----

310 return false; 0
311 ----
312 if (!MI.getOperand(SrcOpIdx1).isReg() || !MI.getOperand(SrcOpIdx2).isReg()) 0
313 // No idea. ----
314 return false; 0
315 return true; 0

387 bool TargetInstrInfo::getStackSlotRange(const TargetRegisterClass *RC, 0
388 unsigned SubIdx, unsigned &Size, ----
389 unsigned &Offset, ----
390 const MachineFunction &MF) const { ----
391 const TargetRegisterInfo *TRI = MF.getSubtarget().getRegisterInfo(); 0
392 if (!SubIdx) { 0
393 Size = TRI->getSpillSize(*RC); 0
394 Offset = 0; 0
395 return true; 0
396 } ----
397 unsigned BitSize = TRI->getSubRegIdxSize(SubIdx); 0
398 // Convert bit size to byte size. ----
399 if (BitSize % 8) 0
400 return false; 0
401 ----
402 int BitOffset = TRI->getSubRegIdxOffset(SubIdx); 0
403 if (BitOffset < 0 || BitOffset % 8) 0
404 return false; 0
405 ----
406 Size = BitSize / 8; 0
407 Offset = (unsigned)BitOffset / 8; 0
408 ----
409 assert(TRI->getSpillSize(*RC) >= (Offset + Size) && "bad subregister range"); 0
410 ----
411 if (!MF.getDataLayout().isLittleEndian()) { 0
412 Offset = TRI->getSpillSize(*RC) - (Offset + Size); 0
413 } ----
414 return true; 0
415 } ----

440 // If the COPY instruction in MI can be folded to a stack operation, return ----
441 // the register class to use. ----
442 static const TargetRegisterClass *canFoldCopy(const MachineInstr &MI, 0
443 unsigned FoldIdx) { ----
444 assert(MI.isCopy() && "MI must be a COPY instruction"); 0
445 if (MI.getNumOperands() != 2) 0
446 return nullptr; 0
447 assert(FoldIdx<2 && "FoldIdx refers no nonexistent operand"); 0
448 ----
449 const MachineOperand &FoldOp = MI.getOperand(FoldIdx); 0
450 const MachineOperand &LiveOp = MI.getOperand(1 - FoldIdx); 0
451 ----
452 if (FoldOp.getSubReg() || LiveOp.getSubReg()) 0
453 return nullptr; 0
454 ----
455 Register FoldReg = FoldOp.getReg(); 0
456 Register LiveReg = LiveOp.getReg(); 0
457 ----
458 assert(FoldReg.isVirtual() && "Cannot fold physregs"); 0
459 ----
460 const MachineRegisterInfo &MRI = MI.getMF()->getRegInfo(); 0
461 const TargetRegisterClass *RC = MRI.getRegClass(FoldReg); 0
462 ----
463 if (LiveOp.getReg().isPhysical()) 0
464 return RC->contains(LiveOp.getReg()) ? RC : nullptr; 0
465 ----
466 if (RC->hasSubClassEq(MRI.getRegClass(LiveReg))) 0
467 return RC; 0
468 ----
469 // FIXME: Allow folding when register classes are memory compatible. ----
470 return nullptr; 0
471 } ----

476 TargetInstrInfo::getPatchpointUnfoldableRange(const MachineInstr &MI) const { 0
477 switch (MI.getOpcode()) { 0
478 case TargetOpcode::STACKMAP: 0
479 // StackMapLiveValues are foldable ----
480 return std::make_pair(0, StackMapOpers(&MI).getVarIdx()); 0
481 case TargetOpcode::PATCHPOINT: 0
482 // For PatchPoint, the call args are not foldable (even if reported in the ----
483 // stackmap e.g. via anyregcc). ----
484 return std::make_pair(0, PatchPointOpers(&MI).getVarIdx()); 0
485 case TargetOpcode::STATEPOINT: 0
486 // For statepoints, fold deopt and gc arguments, but not call arguments. ----
487 return std::make_pair(MI.getNumDefs(), StatepointOpers(&MI).getVarIdx()); 0
488 default: 0
489 llvm_unreachable("unexpected stackmap opcode"); 0
490 } ----
491 } ----

493 static MachineInstr *foldPatchpoint(MachineFunction &MF, MachineInstr &MI, 0
494 ArrayRef Ops, int FrameIndex, ----
495 const TargetInstrInfo &TII) { ----
496 unsigned StartIdx = 0; 0
497 unsigned NumDefs = 0; 0
498 // getPatchpointUnfoldableRange throws guarantee if MI is not a patchpoint. ----
499 std::tie(NumDefs, StartIdx) = TII.getPatchpointUnfoldableRange(MI); 0
500 ----
501 unsigned DefToFoldIdx = MI.getNumOperands(); 0
502 ----
503 // Return false if any operands requested for folding are not foldable (not ----
504 // part of the stackmap's live values). ----
505 for (unsigned Op : Ops) { 0
506 if (Op < NumDefs) { 0
507 assert(DefToFoldIdx == MI.getNumOperands() && "Folding multiple defs"); 0
508 DefToFoldIdx = Op; 0
509 } else if (Op < StartIdx) { 0
510 return nullptr; 0
511 } ----
512 if (MI.getOperand(Op).isTied()) 0
513 return nullptr; 0
514 } ----
515 ----
516 MachineInstr *NewMI = ----
517 MF.CreateMachineInstr(TII.get(MI.getOpcode()), MI.getDebugLoc(), true); 0
518 MachineInstrBuilder MIB(MF, NewMI); 0
519 ----
520 // No need to fold return, the meta data, and function arguments ----
521 for (unsigned i = 0; i < StartIdx; ++i) 0
522 if (i != DefToFoldIdx) 0
523 MIB.add(MI.getOperand(i)); 0
524 ----
525 for (unsigned i = StartIdx, e = MI.getNumOperands(); i < e; ++i) { 0
526 MachineOperand &MO = MI.getOperand(i); 0
527 unsigned TiedTo = e; 0
528 (void)MI.isRegTiedToDefOperand(i, &TiedTo); 0
529 ----
530 if (is_contained(Ops, i)) { 0
531 assert(TiedTo == e && "Cannot fold tied operands"); 0
532 unsigned SpillSize; ----
533 unsigned SpillOffset; ----
534 // Compute the spill slot size and offset. ----
535 const TargetRegisterClass *RC = ----
536 MF.getRegInfo().getRegClass(MO.getReg()); 0
537 bool Valid = ----
538 TII.getStackSlotRange(RC, MO.getSubReg(), SpillSize, SpillOffset, MF); 0
539 if (!Valid) 0
540 report_fatal_error("cannot spill patchpoint subregister operand"); 0
541 MIB.addImm(StackMaps::IndirectMemRefOp); 0
542 MIB.addImm(SpillSize); 0
543 MIB.addFrameIndex(FrameIndex); 0
544 MIB.addImm(SpillOffset); 0
545 } else { ----
546 MIB.add(MO); 0
547 if (TiedTo < e) { 0
548 assert(TiedTo < NumDefs && "Bad tied operand"); 0
549 if (TiedTo > DefToFoldIdx) 0
550 --TiedTo; 0
551 NewMI->tieOperands(TiedTo, NewMI->getNumOperands() - 1); 0
552 } ----
553 } ----
554 } ----
555 return NewMI; 0
556 } ----
557 ----
558 MachineInstr *TargetInstrInfo::foldMemoryOperand(MachineInstr &MI, 0
559 ArrayRef Ops, int FI, ----
560 LiveIntervals *LIS, ----
561 VirtRegMap *VRM) const { ----
562 auto Flags = MachineMemOperand::MONone; 0
563 for (unsigned OpIdx : Ops) 0
564 Flags |= MI.getOperand(OpIdx).isDef() ? MachineMemOperand::MOStore 0
565 : MachineMemOperand::MOLoad; 0
566 ----
567 MachineBasicBlock *MBB = MI.getParent(); 0
568 assert(MBB && "foldMemoryOperand needs an inserted instruction"); 0
569 MachineFunction &MF = *MBB->getParent(); 0
570 ----
571 // If we're not folding a load into a subreg, the size of the load is the ----
572 // size of the spill slot. But if we are, we need to figure out what the ----
573 // actual load size is. ----
574 int64_t MemSize = 0; 0
575 const MachineFrameInfo &MFI = MF.getFrameInfo(); 0
576 const TargetRegisterInfo *TRI = MF.getSubtarget().getRegisterInfo(); 0
577 ----
578 if (Flags & MachineMemOperand::MOStore) { 0
579 MemSize = MFI.getObjectSize(FI); 0
580 } else { ----
581 for (unsigned OpIdx : Ops) { 0
582 int64_t OpSize = MFI.getObjectSize(FI); 0
583 ----
584 if (auto SubReg = MI.getOperand(OpIdx).getSubReg()) { 0
585 unsigned SubRegSize = TRI->getSubRegIdxSize(SubReg); 0
586 if (SubRegSize > 0 && !(SubRegSize % 8)) 0
587 OpSize = SubRegSize / 8; 0
588 } ----
589 ----
590 MemSize = std::max(MemSize, OpSize); 0
591 } ----
592 } ----
593 ----
594 assert(MemSize && "Did not expect a zero-sized stack slot"); 0
595 ----
596 MachineInstr *NewMI = nullptr; 0
597 ----
598 if (MI.getOpcode() == TargetOpcode::STACKMAP || 0
599 MI.getOpcode() == TargetOpcode::PATCHPOINT || 0
600 MI.getOpcode() == TargetOpcode::STATEPOINT) { 0
601 // Fold stackmap/patchpoint. ----
602 NewMI = foldPatchpoint(MF, MI, Ops, FI, *this); 0
603 if (NewMI) 0
604 MBB->insert(MI, NewMI); 0
605 } else { ----
606 // Ask the target to do the actual folding. ----
607 NewMI = foldMemoryOperandImpl(MF, MI, Ops, MI, FI, LIS, VRM); 0
608 } ----
609 ----
610 if (NewMI) { 0
611 NewMI->setMemRefs(MF, MI.memoperands()); 0
612 // Add a memory operand, foldMemoryOperandImpl doesn't do that. ----
613 assert((!(Flags & MachineMemOperand::MOStore) || 0
614 NewMI->mayStore()) && ----
615 "Folded a def to a non-store!"); ----
616 assert((!(Flags & MachineMemOperand::MOLoad) || 0
617 NewMI->mayLoad()) && ----
618 "Folded a use to a non-load!"); ----
619 assert(MFI.getObjectOffset(FI) != -1); 0
620 MachineMemOperand *MMO = ----
621 MF.getMachineMemOperand(MachinePointerInfo::getFixedStack(MF, FI), 0
622 Flags, MemSize, MFI.getObjectAlign(FI)); ----
623 NewMI->addMemOperand(MF, MMO); 0
624 ----
625 // The pass "x86 speculative load hardening" always attaches symbols to ----
626 // call instructions. We need copy it form old instruction. ----
627 NewMI->cloneInstrSymbols(MF, MI); 0
628 ----
629 return NewMI; 0
630 } ----
631 ----
632 // Straight COPY may fold as load/store. ----
633 if (!MI.isCopy() || Ops.size() != 1) 0
634 return nullptr; 0
635 ----
636 const TargetRegisterClass *RC = canFoldCopy(MI, Ops[0]); 0
637 if (!RC) 0
638 return nullptr; 0
639 ----
640 const MachineOperand &MO = MI.getOperand(1 - Ops[0]); 0
641 MachineBasicBlock::iterator Pos = MI; 0
642 ----
643 if (Flags == MachineMemOperand::MOStore) 0
644 storeRegToStackSlot(*MBB, Pos, MO.getReg(), MO.isKill(), FI, RC, TRI, 0
645 Register()); ----
646 else ----
647 loadRegFromStackSlot(*MBB, Pos, MO.getReg(), FI, RC, TRI, Register()); 0
648 return &*--Pos; 0
649 } ----
650 ----
651 MachineInstr *TargetInstrInfo::foldMemoryOperand(MachineInstr &MI, 0
652 ArrayRef Ops, ----
653 MachineInstr &LoadMI, ----
654 LiveIntervals *LIS) const { ----
655 assert(LoadMI.canFoldAsLoad() && "LoadMI isn't foldable!"); 0
656 #ifndef NDEBUG ----
657 for (unsigned OpIdx : Ops) 0
658 assert(MI.getOperand(OpIdx).isUse() && "Folding load into def!"); 0
659 #endif ----
660 ----
661 MachineBasicBlock &MBB = *MI.getParent(); 0
662 MachineFunction &MF = *MBB.getParent(); 0
663 ----
664 // Ask the target to do the actual folding. ----
665 MachineInstr *NewMI = nullptr; 0
666 int FrameIndex = 0; 0
667 ----
668 if ((MI.getOpcode() == TargetOpcode::STACKMAP || 0
669 MI.getOpcode() == TargetOpcode::PATCHPOINT || 0
670 MI.getOpcode() == TargetOpcode::STATEPOINT) && 0
671 isLoadFromStackSlot(LoadMI, FrameIndex)) { 0
672 // Fold stackmap/patchpoint. ----
673 NewMI = foldPatchpoint(MF, MI, Ops, FrameIndex, *this); 0
674 if (NewMI) 0
675 NewMI = &*MBB.insert(MI, NewMI); 0
676 } else { ----
677 // Ask the target to do the actual folding. ----
678 NewMI = foldMemoryOperandImpl(MF, MI, Ops, MI, LoadMI, LIS); 0
679 } ----
680 ----
681 if (!NewMI) 0
682 return nullptr; 0
683 ----
684 // Copy the memoperands from the load to the folded instruction. ----
685 if (MI.memoperands_empty()) { 0
686 NewMI->setMemRefs(MF, LoadMI.memoperands()); 0
687 } else { ----
688 // Handle the rare case of folding multiple loads. ----
689 NewMI->setMemRefs(MF, MI.memoperands()); 0
690 for (MachineInstr::mmo_iterator I = LoadMI.memoperands_begin(), 0
691 E = LoadMI.memoperands_end(); 0
692 I != E; ++I) { 0
693 NewMI->addMemOperand(MF, *I); 0
694 } ----
695 } ----
696 return NewMI; 0
697 } ----
698 ----
699 /// transferImplicitOperands - MI is a pseudo-instruction, and the lowered ----
700 /// replacement instructions immediately precede it. Copy any implicit ----
701 /// operands from MI to the replacement instruction. ----
702 static void transferImplicitOperands(MachineInstr *MI, 0
703 const TargetRegisterInfo *TRI) { ----
704 MachineBasicBlock::iterator CopyMI = MI; 0
705 --CopyMI; 0
706 ----
707 Register DstReg = MI->getOperand(0).getReg(); 0
708 for (const MachineOperand &MO : MI->implicit_operands()) { 0
709 CopyMI->addOperand(MO); 0
710 ----
711 // Be conservative about preserving kills when subregister defs are ----
712 // involved. If there was implicit kill of a super-register overlapping the ----
713 // copy result, we would kill the subregisters previous copies defined. ----
714 ----
715 if (MO.isKill() && TRI->regsOverlap(DstReg, MO.getReg())) 0
716 CopyMI->getOperand(CopyMI->getNumOperands() - 1).setIsKill(false); 0
717 } ----
718 } 0
719 ----
720 void TargetInstrInfo::lowerCopy(MachineInstr *MI, 0
721 const TargetRegisterInfo *TRI) const { ----
722 if (MI->allDefsAreDead()) { 0
723 MI->setDesc(get(TargetOpcode::KILL)); 0
724 return; 0
725 } ----
726 ----
727 MachineOperand &DstMO = MI->getOperand(0); 0
728 MachineOperand &SrcMO = MI->getOperand(1); 0
729 ----
730 bool IdentityCopy = (SrcMO.getReg() == DstMO.getReg()); 0
731 if (IdentityCopy || SrcMO.isUndef()) { 0
732 // No need to insert an identity copy instruction, but replace with a KILL ----
733 // if liveness is changed. ----
734 if (SrcMO.isUndef() || MI->getNumOperands() > 2) { 0
735 // We must make sure the super-register gets killed. Replace the ----
736 // instruction with KILL. ----
737 MI->setDesc(get(TargetOpcode::KILL)); 0
738 return; 0
739 } ----
740 // Vanilla identity copy. ----
741 MI->eraseFromParent(); 0
742 return; 0
743 } ----
744 ----
745 copyPhysReg(*MI->getParent(), MI, MI->getDebugLoc(), DstMO.getReg(), 0
746 SrcMO.getReg(), SrcMO.isKill()); 0
747 ----
748 if (MI->getNumOperands() > 2) 0
749 transferImplicitOperands(MI, TRI); 0
750 MI->eraseFromParent(); 0
751 return; 0
752 } ----
753 ----
754 bool TargetInstrInfo::hasReassociableOperands( 0
755 const MachineInstr &Inst, const MachineBasicBlock *MBB) const { ----
756 const MachineOperand &Op1 = Inst.getOperand(1); 0
757 const MachineOperand &Op2 = Inst.getOperand(2); 0
758 const MachineRegisterInfo &MRI = MBB->getParent()->getRegInfo(); 0
759 ----
760 // We need virtual register definitions for the operands that we will ----
761 // reassociate. ----
762 MachineInstr *MI1 = nullptr; 0
763 MachineInstr *MI2 = nullptr; 0
764 if (Op1.isReg() && Op1.getReg().isVirtual()) 0
765 MI1 = MRI.getUniqueVRegDef(Op1.getReg()); 0
766 if (Op2.isReg() && Op2.getReg().isVirtual()) 0
767 MI2 = MRI.getUniqueVRegDef(Op2.getReg()); 0
768 ----
769 // And at least one operand must be defined in MBB. ----
770 return MI1 && MI2 && (MI1->getParent() == MBB || MI2->getParent() == MBB); 0
771 } ----
772 ----
773 bool TargetInstrInfo::areOpcodesEqualOrInverse(unsigned Opcode1, 0
774 unsigned Opcode2) const { ----
775 return Opcode1 == Opcode2 || getInverseOpcode(Opcode1) == Opcode2; 0
776 } ----
777 ----
778 bool TargetInstrInfo::hasReassociableSibling(const MachineInstr &Inst, 0
779 bool &Commuted) const { ----
780 const MachineBasicBlock *MBB = Inst.getParent(); 0
781 const MachineRegisterInfo &MRI = MBB->getParent()->getRegInfo(); 0
782 MachineInstr *MI1 = MRI.getUniqueVRegDef(Inst.getOperand(1).getReg()); 0
783 MachineInstr *MI2 = MRI.getUniqueVRegDef(Inst.getOperand(2).getReg()); 0
784 unsigned Opcode = Inst.getOpcode(); 0
785 ----
786 // If only one operand has the same or inverse opcode and it's the second ----
787 // source operand, the operands must be commuted. ----
788 Commuted = !areOpcodesEqualOrInverse(Opcode, MI1->getOpcode()) && 0
789 areOpcodesEqualOrInverse(Opcode, MI2->getOpcode()); 0
790 if (Commuted) 0
791 std::swap(MI1, MI2); 0
792 ----
793 // 1. The previous instruction must be the same type as Inst. ----
794 // 2. The previous instruction must also be associative/commutative or be the ----
795 // inverse of such an operation (this can be different even for ----
796 // instructions with the same opcode if traits like fast-math-flags are ----
797 // included). ----
798 // 3. The previous instruction must have virtual register definitions for its ----
799 // operands in the same basic block as Inst. ----
800 // 4. The previous instruction's result must only be used by Inst. ----
801 return areOpcodesEqualOrInverse(Opcode, MI1->getOpcode()) && 0
802 (isAssociativeAndCommutative(*MI1) || 0
803 isAssociativeAndCommutative(*MI1, /* Invert */ true)) && 0
804 hasReassociableOperands(*MI1, MBB) && 0
805 MRI.hasOneNonDBGUse(MI1->getOperand(0).getReg()); 0
806 } ----
807 ----
808 // 1. The operation must be associative and commutative or be the inverse of ----
809 // such an operation. ----
810 // 2. The instruction must have virtual register definitions for its ----
811 // operands in the same basic block. ----
812 // 3. The instruction must have a reassociable sibling. ----
813 bool TargetInstrInfo::isReassociationCandidate(const MachineInstr &Inst, 0
814 bool &Commuted) const { ----
815 return (isAssociativeAndCommutative(Inst) || 0
816 isAssociativeAndCommutative(Inst, /* Invert */ true)) && 0
817 hasReassociableOperands(Inst, Inst.getParent()) && 0
818 hasReassociableSibling(Inst, Commuted); 0
819 } ----
820 ----
821 // The concept of the reassociation pass is that these operations can benefit ----
822 // from this kind of transformation: ----
823 // ----
824 // A = ? op ? ----
825 // B = A op X (Prev) ----
826 // C = B op Y (Root) ----
827 // --> ----
828 // A = ? op ? ----
829 // B = X op Y ----
830 // C = A op B ----
831 // ----
832 // breaking the dependency between A and B, allowing them to be executed in ----
833 // parallel (or back-to-back in a pipeline) instead of depending on each other. ----
834 ----
835 // FIXME: This has the potential to be expensive (compile time) while not ----
836 // improving the code at all. Some ways to limit the overhead: ----
837 // 1. Track successful transforms; bail out if hit rate gets too low. ----
838 // 2. Only enable at -O3 or some other non-default optimization level. ----
839 // 3. Pre-screen pattern candidates here: if an operand of the previous ----
840 // instruction is known to not increase the critical path, then don't match ----
841 // that pattern. ----
842 bool TargetInstrInfo::getMachineCombinerPatterns( 0
843 MachineInstr &Root, SmallVectorImpl &Patterns, ----
844 bool DoRegPressureReduce) const { ----
845 bool Commute; ----
846 if (isReassociationCandidate(Root, Commute)) { 0
847 // We found a sequence of instructions that may be suitable for a ----
848 // reassociation of operands to increase ILP. Specify each commutation ----
849 // possibility for the Prev instruction in the sequence and let the ----
850 // machine combiner decide if changing the operands is worthwhile. ----
851 if (Commute) { 0
852 Patterns.push_back(MachineCombinerPattern::REASSOC_AX_YB); 0
853 Patterns.push_back(MachineCombinerPattern::REASSOC_XA_YB); 0
854 } else { ----
855 Patterns.push_back(MachineCombinerPattern::REASSOC_AX_BY); 0
856 Patterns.push_back(MachineCombinerPattern::REASSOC_XA_BY); 0
857 } ----
858 return true; 0
859 } ----
860 ----
861 return false; 0
862 } ----
863 ----
864 /// Return true when a code sequence can improve loop throughput. ----
865 bool ----
866 TargetInstrInfo::isThroughputPattern(MachineCombinerPattern Pattern) const { 0
867 return false; 0
868 } ----
869 ----
870 std::pair ----
871 TargetInstrInfo::getReassociationOpcodes(MachineCombinerPattern Pattern, 0
872 const MachineInstr &Root, ----
873 const MachineInstr &Prev) const { ----
874 bool AssocCommutRoot = isAssociativeAndCommutative(Root); 0
875 bool AssocCommutPrev = isAssociativeAndCommutative(Prev); 0
876 ----
877 // Early exit if both opcodes are associative and commutative. It's a trivial ----
878 // reassociation when we only change operands order. In this case opcodes are ----
879 // not required to have inverse versions. ----
880 if (AssocCommutRoot && AssocCommutPrev) { 0
881 assert(Root.getOpcode() == Prev.getOpcode() && "Expected to be equal"); 0
882 return std::make_pair(Root.getOpcode(), Root.getOpcode()); 0
883 } ----
884 ----
885 // At least one instruction is not associative or commutative. ----
886 // Since we have matched one of the reassociation patterns, we expect that the ----
887 // instructions' opcodes are equal or one of them is the inversion of the ----
888 // other. ----
889 assert(areOpcodesEqualOrInverse(Root.getOpcode(), Prev.getOpcode()) && 0
890 "Incorrectly matched pattern"); ----
891 unsigned AssocCommutOpcode = Root.getOpcode(); 0
892 unsigned InverseOpcode = *getInverseOpcode(Root.getOpcode()); 0
893 if (!AssocCommutRoot) 0
894 std::swap(AssocCommutOpcode, InverseOpcode); 0
895 ----
896 // The transformation rule (`+` is any associative and commutative binary ----
897 // operation, `-` is the inverse): ----
898 // REASSOC_AX_BY: ----
899 // (A + X) + Y => A + (X + Y) ----
900 // (A + X) - Y => A + (X - Y) ----
901 // (A - X) + Y => A - (X - Y) ----
902 // (A - X) - Y => A - (X + Y) ----
903 // REASSOC_XA_BY: ----
904 // (X + A) + Y => (X + Y) + A ----
905 // (X + A) - Y => (X - Y) + A ----
906 // (X - A) + Y => (X + Y) - A ----
907 // (X - A) - Y => (X - Y) - A ----
908 // REASSOC_AX_YB: ----
909 // Y + (A + X) => (Y + X) + A ----
910 // Y - (A + X) => (Y - X) - A ----
911 // Y + (A - X) => (Y - X) + A ----
912 // Y - (A - X) => (Y + X) - A ----
913 // REASSOC_XA_YB: ----
914 // Y + (X + A) => (Y + X) + A ----
915 // Y - (X + A) => (Y - X) - A ----
916 // Y + (X - A) => (Y + X) - A ----
917 // Y - (X - A) => (Y - X) + A ----
918 switch (Pattern) { 0
919 default: 0
920 llvm_unreachable("Unexpected pattern"); 0
921 case MachineCombinerPattern::REASSOC_AX_BY: 0
922 if (!AssocCommutRoot && AssocCommutPrev) 0
923 return {AssocCommutOpcode, InverseOpcode}; 0
924 if (AssocCommutRoot && !AssocCommutPrev) 0
925 return {InverseOpcode, InverseOpcode}; 0
926 if (!AssocCommutRoot && !AssocCommutPrev) 0
927 return {InverseOpcode, AssocCommutOpcode}; 0
928 break; 0
929 case MachineCombinerPattern::REASSOC_XA_BY: 0
930 if (!AssocCommutRoot && AssocCommutPrev) 0
931 return {AssocCommutOpcode, InverseOpcode}; 0
932 if (AssocCommutRoot && !AssocCommutPrev) 0
933 return {InverseOpcode, AssocCommutOpcode}; 0
934 if (!AssocCommutRoot && !AssocCommutPrev) 0
935 return {InverseOpcode, InverseOpcode}; 0
936 break; 0
937 case MachineCombinerPattern::REASSOC_AX_YB: 0
938 if (!AssocCommutRoot && AssocCommutPrev) 0
939 return {InverseOpcode, InverseOpcode}; 0
940 if (AssocCommutRoot && !AssocCommutPrev) 0
941 return {AssocCommutOpcode, InverseOpcode}; 0
942 if (!AssocCommutRoot && !AssocCommutPrev) 0
943 return {InverseOpcode, AssocCommutOpcode}; 0
944 break; 0
945 case MachineCombinerPattern::REASSOC_XA_YB: 0
946 if (!AssocCommutRoot && AssocCommutPrev) 0
947 return {InverseOpcode, InverseOpcode}; 0
948 if (AssocCommutRoot && !AssocCommutPrev) 0
949 return {InverseOpcode, AssocCommutOpcode}; 0
950 if (!AssocCommutRoot && !AssocCommutPrev) 0
951 return {AssocCommutOpcode, InverseOpcode}; 0
952 break; 0
953 } ----
954 llvm_unreachable("Unhandled combination"); 0
955 } ----
956 ----
957 // Return a pair of boolean flags showing if the new root and new prev operands ----
958 // must be swapped. See visual example of the rule in ----
959 // TargetInstrInfo::getReassociationOpcodes. ----
960 static std::pair mustSwapOperands(MachineCombinerPattern Pattern) { 0
961 switch (Pattern) { 0
962 default: 0
963 llvm_unreachable("Unexpected pattern"); 0
964 case MachineCombinerPattern::REASSOC_AX_BY: 0
965 return {false, false}; 0
966 case MachineCombinerPattern::REASSOC_XA_BY: 0
967 return {true, false}; 0
968 case MachineCombinerPattern::REASSOC_AX_YB: 0
969 return {true, true}; 0
970 case MachineCombinerPattern::REASSOC_XA_YB: 0
971 return {true, true}; 0
972 } ----
973 } ----
974 ----
975 /// Attempt the reassociation transformation to reduce critical path length. ----
976 /// See the above comments before getMachineCombinerPatterns(). ----
977 void TargetInstrInfo::reassociateOps( 0
978 MachineInstr &Root, MachineInstr &Prev, ----
979 MachineCombinerPattern Pattern, ----
980 SmallVectorImpl &InsInstrs, ----
981 SmallVectorImpl &DelInstrs, ----
982 DenseMap &InstrIdxForVirtReg) const { ----
983 MachineFunction *MF = Root.getMF(); 0
984 MachineRegisterInfo &MRI = MF->getRegInfo(); 0
985 const TargetInstrInfo *TII = MF->getSubtarget().getInstrInfo(); 0
986 const TargetRegisterInfo *TRI = MF->getSubtarget().getRegisterInfo(); 0
987 const TargetRegisterClass *RC = Root.getRegClassConstraint(0, TII, TRI); 0
988 ----
989 // This array encodes the operand index for each parameter because the ----
990 // operands may be commuted. Each row corresponds to a pattern value, ----
991 // and each column specifies the index of A, B, X, Y. ----
992 unsigned OpIdx[4][4] = { 0
993 { 1, 1, 2, 2 }, ----
994 { 1, 2, 2, 1 }, ----
995 { 2, 1, 1, 2 }, ----
996 { 2, 2, 1, 1 } ----
997 }; ----
998 ----
999 int Row; ----
1000 switch (Pattern) { 0
1001 case MachineCombinerPattern::REASSOC_AX_BY: Row = 0; break; 0
1002 case MachineCombinerPattern::REASSOC_AX_YB: Row = 1; break; 0
1003 case MachineCombinerPattern::REASSOC_XA_BY: Row = 2; break; 0
1004 case MachineCombinerPattern::REASSOC_XA_YB: Row = 3; break; 0
1005 default: llvm_unreachable("unexpected MachineCombinerPattern"); 0
1006 } ----
1007 ----
1008 MachineOperand &OpA = Prev.getOperand(OpIdx[Row][0]); 0
1009 MachineOperand &OpB = Root.getOperand(OpIdx[Row][1]); 0
1010 MachineOperand &OpX = Prev.getOperand(OpIdx[Row][2]); 0
1011 MachineOperand &OpY = Root.getOperand(OpIdx[Row][3]); 0
1012 MachineOperand &OpC = Root.getOperand(0); 0
1013 ----
1014 Register RegA = OpA.getReg(); 0
1015 Register RegB = OpB.getReg(); 0
1016 Register RegX = OpX.getReg(); 0
1017 Register RegY = OpY.getReg(); 0
1018 Register RegC = OpC.getReg(); 0
1019 ----
1020 if (RegA.isVirtual()) 0
1021 MRI.constrainRegClass(RegA, RC); 0
1022 if (RegB.isVirtual()) 0
1023 MRI.constrainRegClass(RegB, RC); 0
1024 if (RegX.isVirtual()) 0
1025 MRI.constrainRegClass(RegX, RC); 0
1026 if (RegY.isVirtual()) 0
1027 MRI.constrainRegClass(RegY, RC); 0
1028 if (RegC.isVirtual()) 0
1029 MRI.constrainRegClass(RegC, RC); 0
1030 ----
1031 // Create a new virtual register for the result of (X op Y) instead of ----
1032 // recycling RegB because the MachineCombiner's computation of the critical ----
1033 // path requires a new register definition rather than an existing one. ----
1034 Register NewVR = MRI.createVirtualRegister(RC); 0
1035 InstrIdxForVirtReg.insert(std::make_pair(NewVR, 0)); 0
1036 ----
1037 auto [NewRootOpc, NewPrevOpc] = getReassociationOpcodes(Pattern, Root, Prev); 0
1038 bool KillA = OpA.isKill(); 0
1039 bool KillX = OpX.isKill(); 0
1040 bool KillY = OpY.isKill(); 0
1041 bool KillNewVR = true; 0
1042 ----
1043 auto [SwapRootOperands, SwapPrevOperands] = mustSwapOperands(Pattern); 0
1044 ----
1045 if (SwapPrevOperands) { 0
1046 std::swap(RegX, RegY); 0
1047 std::swap(KillX, KillY); 0
1048 } ----
1049 ----
1050 // Create new instructions for insertion. ----
1051 MachineInstrBuilder MIB1 = ----
1052 BuildMI(*MF, MIMetadata(Prev), TII->get(NewPrevOpc), NewVR) 0
1053 .addReg(RegX, getKillRegState(KillX)) 0
1054 .addReg(RegY, getKillRegState(KillY)) 0
1055 .setMIFlags(Prev.getFlags()); 0
1056 ----
1057 if (SwapRootOperands) { 0
1058 std::swap(RegA, NewVR); 0
1059 std::swap(KillA, KillNewVR); 0
1060 } ----
1061 ----
1062 MachineInstrBuilder MIB2 = ----
1063 BuildMI(*MF, MIMetadata(Root), TII->get(NewRootOpc), RegC) 0
1064 .addReg(RegA, getKillRegState(KillA)) 0
1065 .addReg(NewVR, getKillRegState(KillNewVR)) 0
1066 .setMIFlags(Root.getFlags()); 0
1067 ----
1068 setSpecialOperandAttr(Root, Prev, *MIB1, *MIB2); 0
1069 ----
1070 // Record new instructions for insertion and old instructions for deletion. ----
1071 InsInstrs.push_back(MIB1); 0
1072 InsInstrs.push_back(MIB2); 0
1073 DelInstrs.push_back(&Prev); 0
1074 DelInstrs.push_back(&Root); 0
1075 ----
1076 // We transformed: ----
1077 // B = A op X (Prev) ----
1078 // C = B op Y (Root) ----
1079 // Into: ----
1080 // B = X op Y (MIB1) ----
1081 // C = A op B (MIB2) ----
1082 // C has the same value as before, B doesn't; as such, keep the debug number ----
1083 // of C but not of B. ----
1084 if (unsigned OldRootNum = Root.peekDebugInstrNum()) 0
1085 MIB2.getInstr()->setDebugInstrNum(OldRootNum); 0
1086 } 0
1087 ----
1088 void TargetInstrInfo::genAlternativeCodeSequence( 0
1089 MachineInstr &Root, MachineCombinerPattern Pattern, ----
1090 SmallVectorImpl &InsInstrs, ----
1091 SmallVectorImpl &DelInstrs, ----
1092 DenseMap &InstIdxForVirtReg) const { ----
1093 MachineRegisterInfo &MRI = Root.getMF()->getRegInfo(); 0
1094 ----
1095 // Select the previous instruction in the sequence based on the input pattern. ----
1096 MachineInstr *Prev = nullptr; 0
1097 switch (Pattern) { 0
1098 case MachineCombinerPattern::REASSOC_AX_BY: 0
1099 case MachineCombinerPattern::REASSOC_XA_BY: ----
1100 Prev = MRI.getUniqueVRegDef(Root.getOperand(1).getReg()); 0
1101 break; 0
1102 case MachineCombinerPattern::REASSOC_AX_YB: 0
1103 case MachineCombinerPattern::REASSOC_XA_YB: ----
1104 Prev = MRI.getUniqueVRegDef(Root.getOperand(2).getReg()); 0
1105 break; 0
1106 default: 0
1107 llvm_unreachable("Unknown pattern for machine combiner"); 0
1108 } ----
1109 ----
1110 // Don't reassociate if Prev and Root are in different blocks. ----
1111 if (Prev->getParent() != Root.getParent()) 0
1112 return; 0
1113 ----
1114 reassociateOps(Root, *Prev, Pattern, InsInstrs, DelInstrs, InstIdxForVirtReg); 0
1115 } ----
1116 ----
1117 MachineTraceStrategy TargetInstrInfo::getMachineCombinerTraceStrategy() const { 0
1118 return MachineTraceStrategy::TS_MinInstrCount; 0
1119 } ----
1120 ----
1121 bool TargetInstrInfo::isReallyTriviallyReMaterializableGeneric( 0
1122 const MachineInstr &MI) const { ----
1123 const MachineFunction &MF = *MI.getMF(); 0
1124 const MachineRegisterInfo &MRI = MF.getRegInfo(); 0
1125 ----
1126 // Remat clients assume operand 0 is the defined register. ----
1127 if (!MI.getNumOperands() || !MI.getOperand(0).isReg()) 0
1128 return false; 0
1129 Register DefReg = MI.getOperand(0).getReg(); 0
1130 ----
1131 // A sub-register definition can only be rematerialized if the instruction ----
1132 // doesn't read the other parts of the register. Otherwise it is really a ----
1133 // read-modify-write operation on the full virtual register which cannot be ----
1134 // moved safely. ----
1135 if (DefReg.isVirtual() && MI.getOperand(0).getSubReg() && 0
1136 MI.readsVirtualRegister(DefReg)) 0
1137 return false; 0
1138 ----
1139 // A load from a fixed stack slot can be rematerialized. This may be ----
1140 // redundant with subsequent checks, but it's target-independent, ----
1141 // simple, and a common case. ----
1142 int FrameIdx = 0; 0
1143 if (isLoadFromStackSlot(MI, FrameIdx) && 0
1144 MF.getFrameInfo().isImmutableObjectIndex(FrameIdx)) 0
1145 return true; 0
1146 ----
1147 // Avoid instructions obviously unsafe for remat. ----
1148 if (MI.isNotDuplicable() || MI.mayStore() || MI.mayRaiseFPException() || 0
1149 MI.hasUnmodeledSideEffects()) 0
1150 return false; 0
1151 ----
1152 // Don't remat inline asm. We have no idea how expensive it is ----
1153 // even if it's side effect free. ----
1154 if (MI.isInlineAsm()) 0
1155 return false; 0
1156 ----
1157 // Avoid instructions which load from potentially varying memory. ----
1158 if (MI.mayLoad() && !MI.isDereferenceableInvariantLoad()) 0
1159 return false; 0
1160 ----
1161 // If any of the registers accessed are non-constant, conservatively assume ----
1162 // the instruction is not rematerializable. ----
1163 for (const MachineOperand &MO : MI.operands()) { 0
1164 if (!MO.isReg()) continue; 0
1165 Register Reg = MO.getReg(); 0
1166 if (Reg == 0) 0
1167 continue; 0
1168 ----
1169 // Check for a well-behaved physical register. ----
1170 if (Reg.isPhysical()) { 0
1171 if (MO.isUse()) { 0
1172 // If the physreg has no defs anywhere, it's just an ambient register ----
1173 // and we can freely move its uses. Alternatively, if it's allocatable, ----
1174 // it could get allocated to something with a def during allocation. ----
1175 if (!MRI.isConstantPhysReg(Reg)) 0
1176 return false; 0
1177 } else { ----
1178 // A physreg def. We can't remat it. ----
1179 return false; 0
1180 } ----
1181 continue; 0
1182 } ----
1183 ----
1184 // Only allow one virtual-register def. There may be multiple defs of the ----
1185 // same virtual register, though. ----
1186 if (MO.isDef() && Reg != DefReg) 0
1187 return false; 0
1188 ----
1189 // Don't allow any virtual-register uses. Rematting an instruction with ----
1190 // virtual register uses would length the live ranges of the uses, which ----
1191 // is not necessarily a good idea, certainly not "trivial". ----
1192 if (MO.isUse()) 0
1193 return false; 0
1194 } ----
1195 ----
1196 // Everything checked out. ----
1197 return true; 0
1198 } ----
1199 ----
1200 int TargetInstrInfo::getSPAdjust(const MachineInstr &MI) const { 0
1201 const MachineFunction *MF = MI.getMF(); 0
1202 const TargetFrameLowering *TFI = MF->getSubtarget().getFrameLowering(); 0
1203 bool StackGrowsDown = ----
1204 TFI->getStackGrowthDirection() == TargetFrameLowering::StackGrowsDown; 0
1205 ----
1206 unsigned FrameSetupOpcode = getCallFrameSetupOpcode(); 0
1207 unsigned FrameDestroyOpcode = getCallFrameDestroyOpcode(); 0
1208 ----
1209 if (!isFrameInstr(MI)) 0
1210 return 0; 0
1211 ----
1212 int SPAdj = TFI->alignSPAdjust(getFrameSize(MI)); 0
1213 ----
1214 if ((!StackGrowsDown && MI.getOpcode() == FrameSetupOpcode) || 0
1215 (StackGrowsDown && MI.getOpcode() == FrameDestroyOpcode)) 0
1216 SPAdj = -SPAdj; 0
1217 ----
1218 return SPAdj; 0
1219 } ----
1220 ----
1221 /// isSchedulingBoundary - Test if the given instruction should be ----
1222 /// considered a scheduling boundary. This primarily includes labels ----
1223 /// and terminators. ----
1224 bool TargetInstrInfo::isSchedulingBoundary(const MachineInstr &MI, 0
1225 const MachineBasicBlock *MBB, ----
1226 const MachineFunction &MF) const { ----
1227 // Terminators and labels can't be scheduled around. ----
1228 if (MI.isTerminator() || MI.isPosition()) 0
1229 return true; 0
1230 ----
1231 // INLINEASM_BR can jump to another block ----
1232 if (MI.getOpcode() == TargetOpcode::INLINEASM_BR) 0
1233 return true; 0
1234 ----
1235 // Don't attempt to schedule around any instruction that defines ----
1236 // a stack-oriented pointer, as it's unlikely to be profitable. This ----
1237 // saves compile time, because it doesn't require every single ----
1238 // stack slot reference to depend on the instruction that does the ----
1239 // modification. ----
1240 const TargetLowering &TLI = *MF.getSubtarget().getTargetLowering(); 0
1241 const TargetRegisterInfo *TRI = MF.getSubtarget().getRegisterInfo(); 0
1242 return MI.modifiesRegister(TLI.getStackPointerRegisterToSaveRestore(), TRI); 0
1243 } ----

1249 } ----

1273 bool TargetInstrInfo::getMemOperandWithOffset( 0
1274 const MachineInstr &MI, const MachineOperand *&BaseOp, int64_t &Offset, ----
1275 bool &OffsetIsScalable, const TargetRegisterInfo *TRI) const { ----

1277 unsigned Width; ----
1278 if (!getMemOperandsWithOffsetWidth(MI, BaseOps, Offset, OffsetIsScalable, 0
1279 Width, TRI) || 0

1282 BaseOp = BaseOps.front(); 0
1283 return true; 0

1290 int ----
1291 TargetInstrInfo::getOperandLatency(const InstrItineraryData *ItinData, 0
1292 SDNode *DefNode, unsigned DefIdx, ----
1293 SDNode *UseNode, unsigned UseIdx) const { ----
1294 if (!ItinData || ItinData->isEmpty()) 0
1295 return -1; 0
1296 ----
1297 if (!DefNode->isMachineOpcode()) 0
1298 return -1; 0
1299 ----
1300 unsigned DefClass = get(DefNode->getMachineOpcode()).getSchedClass(); 0
1301 if (!UseNode->isMachineOpcode()) 0
1302 return ItinData->getOperandCycle(DefClass, DefIdx); 0
1303 unsigned UseClass = get(UseNode->getMachineOpcode()).getSchedClass(); 0
1304 return ItinData->getOperandLatency(DefClass, DefIdx, UseClass, UseIdx); 0
1305 } ----

1313 return 1; 0

1316 } ----

1321 ----
1322 unsigned TargetInstrInfo::getNumMicroOps(const InstrItineraryData *ItinData, 0
1323 const MachineInstr &MI) const { ----
1324 if (!ItinData || ItinData->isEmpty()) 0
1325 return 1; 0
1326 ----
1327 unsigned Class = MI.getDesc().getSchedClass(); 0
1328 int UOps = ItinData->Itineraries[Class].NumMicroOps; 0
1329 if (UOps >= 0) 0
1330 return UOps; 0
1331 ----
1332 // The # of u-ops is dynamically determined. The specific target should ----
1333 // override this function to return the right number. ----
1334 return 1; 0
1335 } ----

1337 /// Return the default expected latency for a def based on it's opcode. ----
1338 unsigned TargetInstrInfo::defaultDefLatency(const MCSchedModel &SchedModel, 0
1339 const MachineInstr &DefMI) const { ----
1340 if (DefMI.isTransient()) 0
1341 return 0; 0
1342 if (DefMI.mayLoad()) 0
1343 return SchedModel.LoadLatency; 0
1344 if (isHighLatencyDef(DefMI.getOpcode())) 0
1345 return SchedModel.HighLatency; 0
1346 return 1; 0
1347 } ----

1353 unsigned TargetInstrInfo::getInstrLatency(const InstrItineraryData *ItinData, 0

1357 // still have a MinLatency property, which getStageLatency checks. ----
1358 if (!ItinData) 0
1359 return MI.mayLoad() ? 2 : 1; 0

1361 return ItinData->getStageLatency(MI.getDesc().getSchedClass()); 0
1362 } ----

1364 bool TargetInstrInfo::hasLowDefLatency(const TargetSchedModel &SchedModel, 0
1365 const MachineInstr &DefMI, ----
1366 unsigned DefIdx) const { ----
1367 const InstrItineraryData *ItinData = SchedModel.getInstrItineraries(); 0

1369 return false; 0
1370 ----
1371 unsigned DefClass = DefMI.getDesc().getSchedClass(); 0
1372 int DefCycle = ItinData->getOperandCycle(DefClass, DefIdx); 0
1373 return (DefCycle != -1 && DefCycle <= 1); 0
1374 } ----
1375 ----
1376 std::optional ----
1377 TargetInstrInfo::describeLoadedValue(const MachineInstr &MI, 0
1378 Register Reg) const { ----
1379 const MachineFunction *MF = MI.getMF(); 0
1380 const TargetRegisterInfo *TRI = MF->getSubtarget().getRegisterInfo(); 0
1381 DIExpression *Expr = DIExpression::get(MF->getFunction().getContext(), {}); 0
1382 int64_t Offset; ----
1383 bool OffsetIsScalable; ----
1384 ----
1385 // To simplify the sub-register handling, verify that we only need to ----
1386 // consider physical registers. ----
1387 assert(MF->getProperties().hasProperty( 0
1388 MachineFunctionProperties::Property::NoVRegs)); ----
1389 ----
1390 if (auto DestSrc = isCopyInstr(MI)) { 0
1391 Register DestReg = DestSrc->Destination->getReg(); 0
1392 ----
1393 // If the copy destination is the forwarding reg, describe the forwarding ----
1394 // reg using the copy source as the backup location. Example: ----
1395 // ----
1396 // x0 = MOV x7 ----
1397 // call callee(x0) ; x0 described as x7 ----
1398 if (Reg == DestReg) 0
1399 return ParamLoadedValue(*DestSrc->Source, Expr); 0
1400 ----
1401 // If the target's hook couldn't describe this copy, give up. ----
1402 return std::nullopt; 0
1403 } else if (auto RegImm = isAddImmediate(MI, Reg)) { 0
1404 Register SrcReg = RegImm->Reg; 0
1405 Offset = RegImm->Imm; 0
1406 Expr = DIExpression::prepend(Expr, DIExpression::ApplyOffset, Offset); 0
1407 return ParamLoadedValue(MachineOperand::CreateReg(SrcReg, false), Expr); 0
1408 } else if (MI.hasOneMemOperand()) { 0
1409 // Only describe memory which provably does not escape the function. As ----
1410 // described in llvm.org/PR43343, escaped memory may be clobbered by the ----
1411 // callee (or by another thread). ----
1412 const auto &TII = MF->getSubtarget().getInstrInfo(); 0
1413 const MachineFrameInfo &MFI = MF->getFrameInfo(); 0
1414 const MachineMemOperand *MMO = MI.memoperands()[0]; 0
1415 const PseudoSourceValue *PSV = MMO->getPseudoValue(); 0
1416 ----
1417 // If the address points to "special" memory (e.g. a spill slot), it's ----
1418 // sufficient to check that it isn't aliased by any high-level IR value. ----
1419 if (!PSV || PSV->mayAlias(&MFI)) 0
1420 return std::nullopt; 0
1421 ----
1422 const MachineOperand *BaseOp; ----
1423 if (!TII->getMemOperandWithOffset(MI, BaseOp, Offset, OffsetIsScalable, 0
1424 TRI)) ----
1425 return std::nullopt; 0
1426 ----
1427 // FIXME: Scalable offsets are not yet handled in the offset code below. ----
1428 if (OffsetIsScalable) 0
1429 return std::nullopt; 0
1430 ----
1431 // TODO: Can currently only handle mem instructions with a single define. ----
1432 // An example from the x86 target: ----
1433 // ... ----
1434 // DIV64m $rsp, 1, $noreg, 24, $noreg, implicit-def dead $rax, implicit-def $rdx ----
1435 // ... ----
1436 // ----
1437 if (MI.getNumExplicitDefs() != 1) 0
1438 return std::nullopt; 0
1439 ----
1440 // TODO: In what way do we need to take Reg into consideration here? ----
1441 ----
1442 SmallVector Ops; 0
1443 DIExpression::appendOffset(Ops, Offset); 0
1444 Ops.push_back(dwarf::DW_OP_deref_size); 0
1445 Ops.push_back(MMO->getSize()); 0
1446 Expr = DIExpression::prependOpcodes(Expr, Ops); 0
1447 return ParamLoadedValue(*BaseOp, Expr); 0
1448 } 0
1449 ----
1450 return std::nullopt; 0
1451 } ----
1452 ----
1453 // Get the call frame size just before MI. ----
1454 unsigned TargetInstrInfo::getCallFrameSizeAt(MachineInstr &MI) const { 0
1455 // Search backwards from MI for the most recent call frame instruction. ----
1456 MachineBasicBlock *MBB = MI.getParent(); 0
1457 for (auto &AdjI : reverse(make_range(MBB->instr_begin(), MI.getIterator()))) { 0
1458 if (AdjI.getOpcode() == getCallFrameSetupOpcode()) 0
1459 return getFrameTotalSize(AdjI); 0
1460 if (AdjI.getOpcode() == getCallFrameDestroyOpcode()) 0
1461 return 0; 0
1462 } ----
1463 ----
1464 // If none was found, use the call frame size from the start of the basic ----
1465 // block. ----
1466 return MBB->getCallFrameSize(); 0
1467 } ----
1468 ----
1469 /// Both DefMI and UseMI must be valid. By default, call directly to the ----
1470 /// itinerary. This may be overriden by the target. ----
1471 int TargetInstrInfo::getOperandLatency(const InstrItineraryData *ItinData, 0
1472 const MachineInstr &DefMI, ----
1473 unsigned DefIdx, ----
1474 const MachineInstr &UseMI, ----
1475 unsigned UseIdx) const { ----
1476 unsigned DefClass = DefMI.getDesc().getSchedClass(); 0
1477 unsigned UseClass = UseMI.getDesc().getSchedClass(); 0
1478 return ItinData->getOperandLatency(DefClass, DefIdx, UseClass, UseIdx); 0
1479 } ----
1480 ----
1481 bool TargetInstrInfo::getRegSequenceInputs( 0
1482 const MachineInstr &MI, unsigned DefIdx, ----
1483 SmallVectorImpl &InputRegs) const { ----
1484 assert((MI.isRegSequence() || 0
1485 MI.isRegSequenceLike()) && "Instruction do not have the proper type"); ----
1486 ----
1487 if (!MI.isRegSequence()) 0
1488 return getRegSequenceLikeInputs(MI, DefIdx, InputRegs); 0
1489 ----
1490 // We are looking at: ----
1491 // Def = REG_SEQUENCE v0, sub0, v1, sub1, ... ----
1492 assert(DefIdx == 0 && "REG_SEQUENCE only has one def"); 0
1493 for (unsigned OpIdx = 1, EndOpIdx = MI.getNumOperands(); OpIdx != EndOpIdx; 0
1494 OpIdx += 2) { 0
1495 const MachineOperand &MOReg = MI.getOperand(OpIdx); 0
1496 if (MOReg.isUndef()) 0
1497 continue; 0
1498 const MachineOperand &MOSubIdx = MI.getOperand(OpIdx + 1); 0
1499 assert(MOSubIdx.isImm() && 0
1500 "One of the subindex of the reg_sequence is not an immediate"); ----
1501 // Record Reg:SubReg, SubIdx. ----
1502 InputRegs.push_back(RegSubRegPairAndIdx(MOReg.getReg(), MOReg.getSubReg(), 0
1503 (unsigned)MOSubIdx.getImm())); 0
1504 } ----
1505 return true; 0
1506 } ----
1507 ----
1508 bool TargetInstrInfo::getExtractSubregInputs( 0
1509 const MachineInstr &MI, unsigned DefIdx, ----
1510 RegSubRegPairAndIdx &InputReg) const { ----
1511 assert((MI.isExtractSubreg() || 0
1512 MI.isExtractSubregLike()) && "Instruction do not have the proper type"); ----
1513 ----
1514 if (!MI.isExtractSubreg()) 0
1515 return getExtractSubregLikeInputs(MI, DefIdx, InputReg); 0
1516 ----
1517 // We are looking at: ----
1518 // Def = EXTRACT_SUBREG v0.sub1, sub0. ----
1519 assert(DefIdx == 0 && "EXTRACT_SUBREG only has one def"); 0
1520 const MachineOperand &MOReg = MI.getOperand(1); 0
1521 if (MOReg.isUndef()) 0
1522 return false; 0
1523 const MachineOperand &MOSubIdx = MI.getOperand(2); 0
1524 assert(MOSubIdx.isImm() && 0
1525 "The subindex of the extract_subreg is not an immediate"); ----
1526 ----
1527 InputReg.Reg = MOReg.getReg(); 0
1528 InputReg.SubReg = MOReg.getSubReg(); 0
1529 InputReg.SubIdx = (unsigned)MOSubIdx.getImm(); 0
1530 return true; 0
1531 } ----
1532 ----
1533 bool TargetInstrInfo::getInsertSubregInputs( 0
1534 const MachineInstr &MI, unsigned DefIdx, ----
1535 RegSubRegPair &BaseReg, RegSubRegPairAndIdx &InsertedReg) const { ----
1536 assert((MI.isInsertSubreg() || 0
1537 MI.isInsertSubregLike()) && "Instruction do not have the proper type"); ----
1538 ----
1539 if (!MI.isInsertSubreg()) 0
1540 return getInsertSubregLikeInputs(MI, DefIdx, BaseReg, InsertedReg); 0
1541 ----
1542 // We are looking at: ----
1543 // Def = INSERT_SEQUENCE v0, v1, sub0. ----
1544 assert(DefIdx == 0 && "INSERT_SUBREG only has one def"); 0
1545 const MachineOperand &MOBaseReg = MI.getOperand(1); 0
1546 const MachineOperand &MOInsertedReg = MI.getOperand(2); 0
1547 if (MOInsertedReg.isUndef()) 0
1548 return false; 0
1549 const MachineOperand &MOSubIdx = MI.getOperand(3); 0
1550 assert(MOSubIdx.isImm() && 0
1551 "One of the subindex of the reg_sequence is not an immediate"); ----
1552 BaseReg.Reg = MOBaseReg.getReg(); 0
1553 BaseReg.SubReg = MOBaseReg.getSubReg(); 0
1554 ----
1555 InsertedReg.Reg = MOInsertedReg.getReg(); 0
1556 InsertedReg.SubReg = MOInsertedReg.getSubReg(); 0
1557 InsertedReg.SubIdx = (unsigned)MOSubIdx.getImm(); 0
1558 return true; 0
1559 } ----
1560 ----
1561 // Returns a MIRPrinter comment for this machine operand. ----
1562 std::string TargetInstrInfo::createMIROperandComment( 0
1563 const MachineInstr &MI, const MachineOperand &Op, unsigned OpIdx, ----
1564 const TargetRegisterInfo *TRI) const { ----
1565 ----
1566 if (!MI.isInlineAsm()) 0
1567 return ""; 0
1568 ----
1569 std::string Flags; 0
1570 raw_string_ostream OS(Flags); 0
1571 ----
1572 if (OpIdx == InlineAsm::MIOp_ExtraInfo) { 0
1573 // Print HasSideEffects, MayLoad, MayStore, IsAlignStack ----
1574 unsigned ExtraInfo = Op.getImm(); 0
1575 bool First = true; 0
1576 for (StringRef Info : InlineAsm::getExtraInfoNames(ExtraInfo)) { 0
1577 if (!First) 0
1578 OS << " "; 0
1579 First = false; 0
1580 OS << Info; 0
1581 } 0
1582 ----
1583 return OS.str(); 0
1584 } ----
1585 ----
1586 int FlagIdx = MI.findInlineAsmFlagIdx(OpIdx); 0
1587 if (FlagIdx < 0 || (unsigned)FlagIdx != OpIdx) 0
1588 return ""; 0
1589 ----
1590 assert(Op.isImm() && "Expected flag operand to be an immediate"); 0
1591 // Pretty print the inline asm operand descriptor. ----
1592 unsigned Flag = Op.getImm(); 0
1593 unsigned Kind = InlineAsm::getKind(Flag); 0
1594 OS << InlineAsm::getKindName(Kind); 0
1595 ----
1596 unsigned RCID = 0; 0
1597 if (!InlineAsm::isImmKind(Flag) && !InlineAsm::isMemKind(Flag) && 0
1598 InlineAsm::hasRegClassConstraint(Flag, RCID)) { 0
1599 if (TRI) { 0
1600 OS << ':' << TRI->getRegClassName(TRI->getRegClass(RCID)); 0
1601 } else ----
1602 OS << ":RC" << RCID; 0
1603 } ----
1604 ----
1605 if (InlineAsm::isMemKind(Flag)) { 0
1606 unsigned MCID = InlineAsm::getMemoryConstraintID(Flag); 0
1607 OS << ":" << InlineAsm::getMemConstraintName(MCID); 0
1608 } ----
1609 ----
1610 unsigned TiedTo = 0; 0
1611 if (InlineAsm::isUseOperandTiedToDef(Flag, TiedTo)) 0
1612 OS << " tiedto:$" << TiedTo; 0
1613 ----
1614 return OS.str(); 0
1615 } 0
1616 ----
1617 TargetInstrInfo::PipelinerLoopInfo::~PipelinerLoopInfo() = default; 0
1618 ----
1619 void TargetInstrInfo::mergeOutliningCandidateAttributes( 0
1620 Function &F, std::vector &Candidates) const { ----
1621 // Include target features from an arbitrary candidate for the outlined ----
1622 // function. This makes sure the outlined function knows what kinds of ----
1623 // instructions are going into it. This is fine, since all parent functions ----
1624 // must necessarily support the instructions that are in the outlined region. ----
1625 outliner::Candidate &FirstCand = Candidates.front(); 0
1626 const Function &ParentFn = FirstCand.getMF()->getFunction(); 0
1627 if (ParentFn.hasFnAttribute("target-features")) 0
1628 F.addFnAttr(ParentFn.getFnAttribute("target-features")); 0
1629 if (ParentFn.hasFnAttribute("target-cpu")) 0
1630 F.addFnAttr(ParentFn.getFnAttribute("target-cpu")); 0
1631 ----
1632 // Set nounwind, so we don't generate eh_frame. ----
1633 if (llvm::all_of(Candidates, [](const outliner::Candidate &C) { 0
1634 return C.getMF()->getFunction().hasFnAttribute(Attribute::NoUnwind); 0
1635 })) ----
1636 F.addFnAttr(Attribute::NoUnwind); 0
1637 } 0
1638 ----
1639 outliner::InstrType TargetInstrInfo::getOutliningType( 0
1640 MachineBasicBlock::iterator &MIT, unsigned Flags) const { ----
1641 MachineInstr &MI = *MIT; 0
1642 ----
1643 // NOTE: MI.isMetaInstruction() will match CFI_INSTRUCTION, but some targets ----
1644 // have support for outlining those. Special-case that here. ----
1645 if (MI.isCFIInstruction()) 0
1646 // Just go right to the target implementation. ----
1647 return getOutliningTypeImpl(MIT, Flags); 0
1648 ----
1649 // Be conservative about inline assembly. ----
1650 if (MI.isInlineAsm()) 0
1651 return outliner::InstrType::Illegal; 0
1652 ----
1653 // Labels generally can't safely be outlined. ----
1654 if (MI.isLabel()) 0
1655 return outliner::InstrType::Illegal; 0
1656 ----
1657 // Don't let debug instructions impact analysis. ----
1658 if (MI.isDebugInstr()) 0
1659 return outliner::InstrType::Invisible; 0
1660 ----
1661 // Some other special cases. ----
1662 switch (MI.getOpcode()) { 0
1663 case TargetOpcode::IMPLICIT_DEF: 0
1664 case TargetOpcode::KILL: ----
1665 case TargetOpcode::LIFETIME_START: ----
1666 case TargetOpcode::LIFETIME_END: ----
1667 return outliner::InstrType::Invisible; 0
1668 default: 0
1669 break; 0
1670 } ----
1671 ----
